Maximum Drawdown

Worst case that could happen in the past, Max Drawdown look for the greates movement from the high point to a low point. The higher the maximum drawdown the higher the risk.

In [47]:
# Calculate strategy returns
# so the logic: you taking return of the strategy from the position you taking previously base on the position you take
# you earn returns based on the position you held in the previous time step
# if not shift(1) then it the market return no your return.
# why multiply meanwhile there is a negative in there?
# if the prediction of the market correct you get minus * minus which become profit or plus. So it become strategy return.
data['strategy'] = data.position.shift(1) * data['returns']

# defining a whole process with function so we only need to specify the two SMA parameter
def test_strategy(SMA):
    data = df.copy()
    data['returns'] = np.log(data.price.div(data.price.shift(1)))#creating a return variable
    data['SMA_S'] = data.price.rolling(int(SMA[0])).mean() #taking the first sma parameter
    data['SMA_L'] = data.price.rolling(int(SMA[1])).mean() #taking the second sma parameter
    data.dropna(inplace = True)

    data['position'] = np.where(data['SMA_S'] > data['SMA_L'], 1, -1)# creating a position of a stratey variable
    data['strategy'] = data.position.shift(1) * data['returns']#creating a return of the strategy
    data.dropna(inplace = True)

    return np.exp(data['strategy'].sum()) #return a sum of strategy profit or return if for example $1 is invested
